I have to systems accessing the same share. Sometimes it takes forever until the second machine notices filechanges after the first machine changed something. Any ideas how to change that? up to 5 secs the story is that on the second computer we have a lisp programm running that reads its input from a file. So every second or so, it probes whether the input file exists. But even if it does exist it takes a while for the lisp program to recognize it. But curiously, if we run ls in a shell the file shows up right away, without any delay.

Hey all. I am interested in streaming video with html 5 (if that is possible) but i cannot find any decent resource about this. Is it possible to stream video with html 5? cgcardona: so, the video tag supports streams? i cant' really find any decent documentation for that playing as it downloads.. that means, its basically streaming? but the sender.. never stops sending?

53e9c7f51ef86a3ed2577bd23d27cdf1: Are you talking about live streaming?  Because I'm pretty sure <video> will start playing as it downloads. That's default behavior AFAIK Well, the data is sent in packets by your server until all the packets have made it to the viewer. Browsers will continue to download, but not block playing of the portion which has been downloaded already As for live, continuous streaming without a definitive endpoint, I have no idea how that would work right now.  WebRTC is the soon-to-arrive feature which could make that possible: https://sites.google.com/site/webrtc/

When I'm adding a feature or something and find I want to do some unrelated cleanup first, I sometimes do the cleanup and then use git add -i to commit only some of the changes, then proceed. I guess I could use git stash instead, but it seems less convenient and more error-prone (e.g., more likely to cause merge conflicts). I'm really curious to know if people have examples of real-world (malicious, not proof-of-concept) MITM attacks on the web. Maybe they've been averted by the fact that even incompetent banks/e-commerce sites/whatever tend to use HTTPS. So they get the little padlock, or to comply with some industry certification or law or something, I don't know. I guess. Also: http://www.ex-parrot.com/pete/upside-down-ternet.html None of this is malicious, though, or something web developers have to worry about in practice. Most web developers, I mean. Well, you can't do anything in that case. Because one, they can probably forge an SSL certificate. As long as they have at least one root CA in their country. And two, they can still tell what IP address you're connecting to, so unless it's a big shared host or you're using something else like TOR, they can still tell where you're going. Which is enough for them to jail you already, if they felt like it. No, you need some form of indirection as well.  It's still a MITM attack, though. And worth pointing out.  If you're trying to hide your activities from the government, and they can get enough info to arrest you or search your computer anyway, then the technology isn't helping. Well, yes.  Everyone in the chain (if by that you mean the path between client and server) is a MITM. If they bother. Anyway, against repressive governments you've pretty much lost from the start.  You need social solutions to that, not technical. I mean, even if you used TOR, they could throw you in jail or ransack your house or whatever just for that. Modern, well-organized governments are essentially invincible to any kind of internal revolt, other than a military coup. I guess you can pressure them in some ways, but technology isn't going to much help you to hide from them.  It does help make it harder for them to control information, though. . . . anyway.  Whatever the case may be, any security scenario where you're trying to defend against a government or comparably powerful organization needs to be treated as an entirely separate category. It shouldn't even be brought up in general, if it's just a general web security discussion. Yep.  I'd still like to see one real-world (malicious, non-government) case, though.  :) "Every so often I receive extremely irate e-mails from people claiming that my Kittenwar site is playing host to some kind of nefarious virus preventing them from accessing the web, accusing me of practising all sorts of dark arts - to which I politely respond that I'm terribly sorry, but this only usually happens to people who are using someone else's wireless connection, and pointing them in the direction of your site. This has happened doz ens of times over the last few years, and you know what? None of them have ever got back to me after I point this out." Hahaha.

So it might be hard to find actual examples, simply because the ecosystem is so defensive against it in the first place. We do have federal wiretapping in the US.  That's passive MITM as far as we know, no changes being done to the stream, but it's a definite example of the scenario. And in terms of personal attacks, Hixie commits MITM attacks against people using his network on occasion.  Just when they're abusing it, and nothing bad, but again, that's an attack scenario. Anyone using a wifi connection they don't own is subject to the owner doing things like that. Yeah, very similar. Authoritarian governments doing wiretapping is something that a web author interested in privacy has to worry about. That's not the average author, but still. Okay, true. Yeah, but that's a separate security issue entirely. Encryption can't help with that at all. What, peeping your IP?  Not necessarily.  Everyone in the chain knows your IP. Okay, yeah, you're right. True. So we're back to (a) open wifi means that the owner can snoop and alter your traffic easily and (b) anyone in the normal chain of routers between you and the target can do the same. But right now, SSL's security against MITM and general ubiquity in cases where MITM would be a profitable exploit means that actual example of MITM are necessarily going to be few and far between. should have been references: http://lists.w3.org/Archives/Public/public-html/2009Dec/0173.html and http://lists.w3.org/Archives/Public/public-html/2009Dec/0174.html and TBL never wanted an IMG element wonders if b5953de161e07c36c49c96a3c48a128d knows the history of "HTML Plus" the W3C has a long history of fucking up HTML by going off into la-la land for a few years while the world evolves without them HTML+ was one such effort (between HTML 1.0 and HTML 2.0) HTML 2.0 was basically "hey, let's see what browsers have actually implemented while we weren't looking" then they made HTML 3.0, which was similarly delusional then they threw that away and made HTML 3.2, which was basically "hey, let's see what else browsers have actually implmeented while we were busy masturbating" then they made HTML 4.0, which shockingly wasn't completely horrible (though it was horribly underspecified) then they gave up on HTML altogether, to the point of ignoring all W3C process and refusing to issue errata or integrate existing errata into point releases and started whole hog on XHTML XHTML 1.0 is literally HTML 4 + a few useless slashes oh, and a new MIME type and draconian error handling, which nobody uses (hi Sam) then XHTML 1.1, which nobody uses then XHTML 2, which they spent almost a decade on and finally put out to pasture this year HTML5 was a community-led effort of browser vendors, standards wonks (like Hixie), and other interested parties all formerly quite active within the W3C they begged and pleaded with the W3C to let them work on HTML5 (or 4.1, or whatever, anything but XHTML 2) the W3C said no so they formed their own working group (WHATWG) and started from scratch (since the license of the HTML 4 specification forbids derivative works by non-W3C organizations) snippets, etc. but defining a new syntax "on top of" HTML in terms of a byte stream is just insane http://diveintomark.org/archives/2009/11/02/why-do-we-have-an-img-element is fun related reading on the history of HTML it (and the rest of this stuff) will form the basis of the introductory chapter of http://diveintohtml5.org/ indeed yes it would appear that the current HTML+RDFa effort has zero chance of producing a good specification and if RDFa sees enough implementation, we'll need to do an RDFa5 retro-spec in a few years which will consist of reverse engineering google's implementation (or whoever ends up being the dominant consumer of RDFa on the public web) i'm not a fan of microdata either it's a decent enough solution to the stated problem i'm just not a fan of the stated 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: RFC 2781 disagrees with you. what do current browsers do? that is, is it really harmless for existing doctype sniffing and all that? since the BOM arises naturally, it is really really dumb for an author to specify the endianness on the HTTP level. no gain and a possibility to get it wrong I guess I should write test cases before discussing this further, but it would be nice not to violate RFCs gratuitously if real-world compat doesn't require doing so it requires the BOM not to have effect, i.e. the decoded stream to include it if the HTML layer wants to chop it off after that, it is being weird of course, this whole thing is about a labeling case that authors should avoid anyway exactly for issues like this as for encoding layer errors vs. html layer errors, I think the spec should do some hand holding for implementors here, because we cannot assume every parser implementor to be a spec lawyer as well what if the HTTP-level label is UTF-16 and the byte stream has two leading BOMs? the decoded character stream then has one BOM. should the HTML layer drop it? hmm. I guess my view here is biased by decoder implementations that do drop the BOM in the decoder when the label says UTF-16. anyway, I think this needs test cases to figure out what the current crop of browsers does and then a bit of spec elaboration plus test cases to help implementors mumbles something about UTF-8 being the one true encoding and UTF-16 and UTF-32 being time sinks for diligent implementors 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: gzip and a very large chunk of characters in CJK HTML is markup and, therefore, in the Basic Latin block

not sure what browsers do. I imagine they ignore the BOM though. looks like rfc2781 make it moot what the html5 spec says, as it is then a violation at the encoding layer, not the parser layer the rfc doesn't require anything of the UAs as far as i can tell i think that in any case a leading BOM should be stripped, whether it is compliant or not it would be the height of uselessness to have the BOM, which authors can't see, imply a <body> i would be a "gotcha" whose only clear purpose was to confuse authors, in an area where authors can barely understand what's going on anyway regarding whether it's an error or not, that's only a conformance checker matter really the UTF-16 RFC doesn't as far as i can tell require the leading BOM to be stripped before sending it to the next layer I would say that only the HTML (application) layer strips the BOM b8810fee2f4a71f849f3f7409546d1d9: fair enough b8810fee2f4a71f849f3f7409546d1d9: (note that UTF-8 is not really great for CJK)

ef6f2287bae00ba79475fbf56c2b6fee: There's indeed tension between saying "this stuff sucks so you shouldn't use it for new content" and "this stuff sucks so badly that you should go and remove if from the content you are upgrading" ef6f2287bae00ba79475fbf56c2b6fee: I think we don't have a good solution that respects both the time of upgraders and of authors starting from a clean slate ef6f2287bae00ba79475fbf56c2b6fee: the problem is how to distinguish them in a way that doesn't fail like HTML 4.01 Strict vs. Transitional? ef6f2287bae00ba79475fbf56c2b6fee: it seems a bit pointless to make the validator emit messages at all where the messages are meant to be ignored ef6f2287bae00ba79475fbf56c2b6fee: I'm getting into the game of analyzing millions of pages in order to get data about what kind of errors are the ones that would particularly waste the time of upgraders ef6f2287bae00ba79475fbf56c2b6fee: as far as HTML tables and IE installed base are concerned, we have that kind of problem with HTML5 fwiw, I'm not so much concerned about pushing an ideal of good practice I'm more interested in producing a tool that allows authors catch mistakes they didn't make although Validator.nu does have political good practice aspects oops didn't *intend* to make ef6f2287bae00ba79475fbf56c2b6fee: if you use <embed> in HTML 4.01 on purpose, for example edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e: I guess the point on my side is that I don't believe as much in the wishful part of conformance as I think Hixie does edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e: when it comes to removing "bad" legacy features from the conforming language ef6f2287bae00ba79475fbf56c2b6fee: that's not what making align on td non-conforming is about, though I stopped paying attention to CSS validation when I couldn't configure the validator to grok Prince extensions edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e: this was the CSS validator running inside Oxygen or spaces in URLs most of the time edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e: what do I have stats on? well, one could actually differentiate between the two whether it's good to do so or not I don't know. b8810fee2f4a71f849f3f7409546d1d9: for example one could error in response to &gt= but only warn for &name= b8810fee2f4a71f849f3f7409546d1d9: warnings aren't "meant to be ignored". b8810fee2f4a71f849f3f7409546d1d9: I think the "failure" (if there was one) had to do with choices about what went into strict that disagreed with what authors wanted to use and that worked in the browsers they cared about. b8810fee2f4a71f849f3f7409546d1d9: I suppose target and iframe being the most important examples. a924fb58d2c25874322f4e5126f608b9: Well of course not. Authors wanting to use doesn't make it a great idea. depends on what the point of the versioning is if the point of conformance is to get "good practice" but you can only get conformance by sanctioning "bad practice" that's a largely pointless exercise. what are "mistakes they didn't make"? how can you intend to make a mistake? is that good or bad? using a "bad practice" on purpose. that's not a "mistake". that's a conformance error. or an instance of deliberate non-conformance validators can't really do much about instances of deliberate non-conformance the point for me, is increasing puzzlement about what conformance in HTML5 is, and its integrity as a single thing. it seems to me the one bit of conformance everyone (?) would buy into is where you recommend features that work in lots of user agents over features that do the same thing but in fewer user agents. Hixie seems keen to use conformance to protect future extension points, which is a good idea, but of less widespread appeal. edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e: CSS has extension points built into the language. edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e: I don't think CSS validation/conformance has been a particularly powerful force for authors. e.g. non-validating hacks, opacity, filter, vendor-specific extensions with the last one built-in, but forbidden Then there's conformance for trying to change authoring practices that could lead to errors, even when they in fact aren't errors that cause problems. e.g. &name in href. While I'm glad of a tool to check that, I suspect that will reduce the amount of conformance considerably. e.g. lots of relatively conforming webpages fail to encode ampersands now edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e: yeah well I'm talking about &name= not &name; and if one didn't require ; that would break _old_ content using &name= of which there's plenty yeah. they _might_. personally, I don't care whether it's conforming or not particularly (I just use &amp; ). I just think it's interesting as an aspect of the emerging picture of HTML5 conformance. my guess (it's only a guess) is that there will be more websites failing conformance because of ampersand rules than would if HTML5 required alt (for example), since I see lots of websites with alt but that fail to encode ampersands Flickr probably won't conform whatever the conformance rules are (alt isn't a "problem" for Flickr now, it just uses alt="" on the main photo page; it doesn't encode ampersands however). given those speculations, I find much of the alt debate rather odd oh there are other odd things said by most correspondents b8810fee2f4a71f849f3f7409546d1d9: websites with/without alt, with/without ampersands encoded properly, combinations thereof, I think? oh, pages is somewhat different e.g. photo sharing sites have lots of pages, few links. note I said "websites failing conformance"

solarce, what do you mean with "use LDAP to query a DC"? Normally winbind is used to map the users of the AD with local IDs and these accounts are accessed through NSS and PAM but you still have the local password files available to use with only local users point one, I whould not say thats impossible, but anyway, normally LDAP is used to store the mappings if you want to use the same mappings in multiple domain members, as winbind maps the accounts as they are seen hmm, you can extend the AD schema with AD4Unix too and store unix account information there too, but anyway I dont know how many people do that where did you saw that way of query AD with LDAP? with multiple clients you can for example, store the idmap mappings in an ldap server, and make the clients use that mapping through winbind to make it the same for all clients without that the same AD user will have different unix IDs in every system well, if you want that these ADs accounts be valid only in the FC4 server, winbind is only necessary in that server to that accounts be valid locally in the server, it must be correctly configured in PAM and NSS but I never tested these accounts being used to access resources in a domain member but they works well in ssh, gdm, etc normally its configured in the /etc/pam.d/login file thers a ssh file too you can compare them and see if only login includes a pam_winbind module for authentication if you really use winbind depends of the system, some distribution allow the use of "includes" and you can configure it once in a file for all services
